{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || 11\n|-\n! [[Anna Paquin]]\n| || || || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || || || || {{tick}} || || || 3\n|-\n! [[Evan Peters]]\n| || || || || || || || || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || || 2\n|-\n! [[Rebecca Romijn]]\n| || || || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || || || || || || || 2\n|-\n! [[Newton Thomas Sigel]]\n| || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || 10\n|-\n! [[Kevin Spacey]]\n| || || {{tick}} || || || || {{tick}} || || || || || || 2\n|-\n! [[Patrick Stewart]]\n| || || || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || || || || {{tick}} || || || 3\n|-\n! [[Lucas Till]]\n| || || || || || || || || || {{tick}} || {{tick}} || || 2\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Work\n! Award\n! Category\n! Result\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1993\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Public Access]]''\n| [[Sundance Film Festival]]\n| Grand Jury Prize\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Deauville American Film Festival]]\n| International Critics' prize\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1995\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n| [[Tokyo International Film Festival]]\n| Silver prize\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Seattle International Film Festival]]\n| Best Director\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1996\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n| [[1st Empire Awards|Empire Awards]]\n| Best Newcomer\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[23rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| Himself\n| Saturn Award\n| President's Memorial Award\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Apt Pupil (film)|Apt Pupil]]''\n| [[25th Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2001\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''\n| [[6th Empire Awards|Empire Awards]]\n| Best Director\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[27th Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| rowspan=\"1\" | ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''\n| Prix Nebula\n| Best Script\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]''\n| [[30th Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Superman Returns]]''\n| [[12th Empire Awards|Empire Awards]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[33rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]''\n| [[35th Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''\n| [[41st Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]''\n| [[43rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|}\n{{small|Note: Singer was initially listed as a nominee for [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film|Best British Film]] at the [[British Academy Film Awards]] for ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]'' as a co-producer in [[72nd British Academy Film Awards|2019]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Outstanding British Film |url=http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/ee-british-academy-film-awards-nominees-winners-2019#outstanding-british-film |publisher=[[British Academy Film Awards]] |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> however following sexual assault allegations the Academy announced that they had rescinded his nomination.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bryan Singer's Name Removed From BAFTA Nomination for 'Bohemian Rhapsody' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/bryan-singers-name-removed-from-bafta-nomination-for-bohemian-rhapsody/amp/ |publisher=The Wrap |accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1741}}\n*{{IMDb company|id=0057712|company=Bad Hat Harry Productions}}\n\n{{Bryan Singer}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Bryan Singer\n|list =\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Newcomer}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singer, Bryan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Director Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Newcomer Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:LGBT directors]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:People from West Windsor Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South alumni]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Visual Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Fantasy film directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:LGBT screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American film director, writer and producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bryan Singer\n| image = Brian Singer \"International Competition Jury\" at Opening Ceremony of the 28th Tokyo International Film Festival (22427114066) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Singer at the 28th [[Tokyo International Film Festival]] in 2015\n| birth_name = Bryan Jay Singer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1965|9|17}}\n| birth_place = New York City\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Director\n* producer\n* writer\n}}\n| years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| known_for        = \n   {{ubl\n    |''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n    |''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''\n    |''[[X2 (film)|X2: X-Men United]]''\n    |''[[Superman Returns]]''\n    |''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]''\n    |''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''\n    |''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]''\n    |''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]''\n   }}\n| children =  1\n}}\n\n'''Bryan Jay Singer''' (born September 17, 1965)<ref name=filmref/> is an American director, producer and writer of film and television. He is the founder of [[Bad Hat Harry Productions]] and has produced or co-produced almost all of the films he has directed.\n\nAfter graduating from the University of Southern California, Singer directed his first short film, ''[[Lion's Den (1988 film)|Lion's Den]]'' (1988). On the basis of that film, he received financing for his next film, ''[[Public Access]]'' (1993), which was a co-winner of the Grand Jury Prize at the 1993 [[Sundance Film Festival]]. In the mid-1990s, Singer received critical acclaim for directing the neo-noir crime thriller ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'' (1995), which starred [[Gabriel Byrne]], [[Kevin Spacey]], [[Stephen Baldwin]], and [[Benicio del Toro]]. He followed this with another thriller, ''[[Apt Pupil (film)|Apt Pupil]]'' (1998), an adaptation of a [[Stephen King]] novella about a boy's fascination with a Nazi war criminal. In the 2000s, he became known for big budget superhero films such as ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]'' (2000), for which Singer won the 2000 [[Saturn Award for Best Direction]], its sequel ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]'' (2003), and ''[[Superman Returns]]'' (2006). He then directed the World War II historical thriller ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]'' (2008), co-wrote/co-produced ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'' (2011), and directed the fantasy adventure film ''[[Jack the Giant Slayer]]'' (2013), as well as two more ''X-Men'' films, ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'' (2014) and ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]'' (2016). Singer also directed the [[Queen (band)|Queen]] biographical film ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]'' (2018), although he was fired from the film shortly before its completion.\n\nSince 1997, a number of boys and men have alleged that Singer sexually assaulted them as [[Minor (law)|minors]]. Singer has denied all of the allegations. The [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] removed Singer's name from ''Bohemian Rhapsody's'' 2019 nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film]] because of the allegations against him.\n\n==Early life==\nSinger was born in New York City and was adopted by Grace Sinden, an environmental activist, and Norbert Dave Singer, a corporate executive.<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/75/Bryan-Singer.html|title=Bryan Singer biography|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}</ref> He grew up in a Jewish household in [[West Windsor Township, New Jersey]]. In his early teens, he started making 8mm films as well as experimenting with photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/alex-simon/great-conversations-bryan_b_7465494.html|title=Great Conversations: Bryan Singer|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=May 28, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[West Windsor-Plainsboro High School South|West Windsor-Plainsboro High School]], graduating in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|archivedate=January 25, 2008|author=Miller, Lynn|url=http://www.wwpinfo.com/default.asp?smenu=75&sdetail=2578|title=More West Windsor Filmmaking Stars on the Horizon|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125073606/http://www.wwpinfo.com/default.asp?smenu=75&sdetail=2578|date=January 25, 2008|work=West Windsor & Plainsboro News|quote=Two West Windsor-Plainsboro High School graduates are following in the footsteps of two other filmmakers from West Windsor, Bryan Singer and Christopher McQuarrie. Singer, Class of 1984, and McQuarrie, Class of 1986, have recently joined together for the filming of \"Valkyrie\", a controversial film about Colonel Claus Schenk von Stauffenberg, the German Army officer who tried to do away with Hitler during World War II.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Berrin, Danielle|url=http://jewishjournal.com/uncategorized/77685/|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|The Jewish Journal]]|title=How Auschwitz, \"X-Men\" and its Jewish director changed comics|date=March 18, 2010}}</ref> He studied filmmaking for two years at the [[School of Visual Arts]] in New York, and later transferred to the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]] in Los Angeles where he followed the Critical studies program.<ref>{{cite news|author=Weinraub, Bernard|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06E1D91039F93AA35754C0A9669C8B63|title=FILM; An Unusual Choice for the Role of Studio Superhero|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 9, 2000|accessdate=November 27, 2007|quote=As a child, Mr. Singer grew up in Princeton Junction, N.J. His father, Norbert Singer, is a businessman and his mother, Grace, is an environmental activist and former state environmental official. Mr. Singer attended the School of Visual Arts in Manhattan for two years, and then transferred to the University of Southern California.}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1980s\u20131990s===\nSinger directed a short film in 1988 called ''Lion's Den'' involving a number of friends, including actor [[Ethan Hawke]], whom he knew from his childhood in New Jersey, and editor [[John Ottman]], whom he had met while working on a friend's short film.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Ottman|url=http://www.johnottman.com/projects/edited/lionsden|title=Projects \u2013 Lion's Den|work=johnottman.com|accessdate=January 2, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229044354/http://www.johnottman.com/projects/edited/lionsden/|archive-date=December 29, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Ottman|url=http://www.johnottman.com/projects/edited/summer|title=Projects \u2013 Summer Rain|work=johnottman.com|accessdate=January 2, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229044359/http://www.johnottman.com/projects/edited/summer/|archive-date=December 29, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> After a screening of ''Lion's Den'', Singer was approached by someone from Tokuma Japan Productions, a Japanese company interested in funding a series of low-budget films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuvein.com/directedby/bryansinger.html|title=Focus|author=Dau, Carsten|year=2001|publisher=Directed By Online|accessdate=May 19, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210142614/http://www.nuvein.com/directedby/bryansinger.html|archivedate=December 10, 2010}}</ref> Singer pitched a concept that eventually became the film ''[[Public Access]]'' (1993). Ottman again served as editor but this time also composed the score for the film. At the 1993 [[Sundance Film Festival]], the film was named as co-winner of the [[Grand Jury Prize]] with [[Ruby in Paradise]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/5009328.stm|title=Comic book crusader: Bryan Singer|author=Staff|date=July 13, 2006|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=May 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, he founded the production company Bad Hat Harry Productions, in homage to [[Steven Spielberg]] and the famous line from ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''. Singer followed this by directing ''The Usual Suspects'', which was screened out of competition at the [[1995 Cannes Film Festival]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} It was a success, winning [[Christopher McQuarrie]] an [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Original Screenplay)]], and actor [[Kevin Spacey]] an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn 1998, Singer obtained the rights to adapt [[Stephen King]]'s novella ''[[Apt Pupil]]'', a thriller about an all-American boy discovering that a [[Nazi]] war criminal lives in his neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|first=Donald|last=Clarke|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/carrie-on-screaming-the-20-best-stephen-king-movies-1.3180611|title=Carrie on screaming: the 20 best Stephen King movies|work=[[The Irish Times]]|date=August 12, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> Singer's [[Apt Pupil (film)|film adaptation]] starred Sir [[Ian McKellen]], [[Brad Renfro]], and [[David Schwimmer]].\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:BryanSinger edited.jpg|thumb|200px|Singer in Comic Con 2006, promoting ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'']]\nIn the early 2000s, Singer was hoping to direct ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'' based on the [[Chuck Barris]] book of the same name.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kehr, Dave|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/03/movies/at-the-movies.html|title=AT THE MOVIES|work=The New York Times|date=January 3, 2003|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> The film was later directed by [[George Clooney]] for [[Miramax Films]] with [[Sam Rockwell]] in the lead role. In February 2001, Singer was attempting to produce a new ''[[Battlestar Galactica]]'' television series for [[Universal Television|Studios USA]] (now [[NBC Universal]] Television Studio) Speaking to ''[[BBC News]]'', Singer said he was \"confident that the ''Galactica'' brand is a sleeping giant. It was a show I watched during its initial run, from the pilot to the final episode. The essence and the brand name is quite potent in a climate where there's a great deficit of sci-fi programming.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1185914.stm|title=Battlestar Galactica set for TV return|date=February 23, 2001|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|location=London, England|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> Singer eventually left the project, which was produced by another team on the [[Syfy|Sci Fi Channel]].\n\nIn mid-2004, Singer was in negotiations to direct ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'' for Fox, when Singer agreed to direct ''[[Superman Returns]]'' for [[Warner Bros.]]. In consequence, Fox terminated its production deal with Bad Hat Harry Productions, Singer's production company.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lisa|last=Foreman|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/thr/film/brief_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000601138 |title=Fox breaks off film deal with helmer Singer|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 6, 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040815040621/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/film/brief_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000601138|archivedate=August 15, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''Superman Returns'' was filmed in Australia in 2005, and was released on June 28, 2006. Singer claimed that he had always admired and identified with the character, citing the fact that he and Superman are both orphans, noting that he was inspired by [[Superman (1978 film)|the 1978 film]] starring [[Christopher Reeve]] and the comics of [[Alex Ross]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Epstein|first=Daniel Robert|url=http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Bryan+Singer+director+of+Superman+Returns|title=Bryan Singer director of Superman Returns|date=May 3, 2006|work=SuicideGirls.com|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Bryan Singer.2776 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Singer at the premiere of ''[[Valkyrie (film)|Valkyrie]]'' in 2009]]\n\nIn August 2009, Universal Pictures announced that Singer would direct and produce a big screen reimagining of the ''[[Battlestar Galactica]]'' [[Battlestar Galactica (1978 TV series)|television series]] of the late-1970s, which would not draw any material from the Syfy Channel [[Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series)|reimagined series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/08/13/bryan-singer-battlestar-galactica-movie|title=Bryan Singer to direct and produce 'Battlestar Galactica' movie|first=Nicole|last=Sperling|website=[[Hollywood Insider]]|date=August 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817005516/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2009/08/13/bryan-singer-battlestar-galactica-movie|archivedate=August 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2009, it was announced NBC has partnered with Singer and [[Bryan Fuller]] to adapt [[Augusten Burroughs]]'s ''[[Sellevision]]'' into a series about a fictional home shopping network, according to ''The Hollywood Reporter''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joyce|last=Eng|title=Bryan Fuller, Bryan Singer Team Up with NBC for Sellevision|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Bryan-Fuller-Bryan-1009559.aspx|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> Neither project was ultimately produced.\n\nAt the premiere of [[James Cameron]]'s ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' on December 16, 2009, Singer confirmed that he would be directing ''[[Jack the Giant Slayer]]'' (2013) for Warner Bros, and that he had signed on to do ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspace.com/officialavatarmovie|title=Avatar|publisher=MySpace|date=November 26, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://superherohype.com/news/x-mennews.php?id=8929|title=Super Hero Hype \u2013 Bryan Singer Will Direct X-Men: First Class!|author=Edward Douglas|date=December 17, 2009}}</ref> but conflicts between the two projects led to Singer being only a producer and co-screenwriter on ''First Class'',<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike|title=Bryan Singer Producing 'X-Men: First Class'|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 26, 2010|url=https://www.deadline.com/2010/03/singer-to-producex-men-first-class|accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> with [[Matthew Vaughn]] taking over directorial duties.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike|title=Fox Signs Vaughn To Direct 'X-Men: First Class' And Sets June 3, 2011 Release Date|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 4, 2010|url=https://www.deadline.com/2010/05/fox-seals-deal-for-matthew-vaughn-to-direct-x-men-first-class/#more-38098|accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nIn October 2012, it was announced that Singer would direct the next movie in the series, ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''; Vaughn stayed on as a producer and screenwriter, and the film was released in May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni39580891/|title=Bryan Singer will direct 'X-Men: Days of Future Past'|first=Adam B.|last=Vary}}</ref> Singer produced the commercials for the ice cream [[Magnum (ice cream)|Magnum Gold]], which featured [[Benicio del Toro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themarketingsite.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=12565|title=NEW Magnum Gold?! is as Good as Gold}}</ref> In 2012, Singer was the executive producer alongside [[Jane Lynch]] of the short film, ''Ronny and I'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/watch-vibrant-trailer-for-bryan-singer-jane-lynch-produced-coming-of-age-cannes-short-ronny-and-i|title=Watch: Bryan Singer and Jane Lynch Present Exclusive Trailer|first=Cameron|last=Sinz|date=April 29, 2013|work=Indiewire|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> directed by Guy Shalem that screened at Outfest and Cannes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outfest.org/tixSYS/2013/xslguide/eventnote?notepg=1&EventNumber=3797&|title=Ronny and I \u2013 2013 Outfest|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmpulse.net/cannes-2013-ronny-i-trailer/|title=Cannes 2013: 'Ronny & i' Trailer |work=Film Pulse|date=April 29, 2013|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> Singer directed another X-Men film, ''[[X-Men: Apocalypse]]'',<ref>{{cite web|first=Silas|last=Lesnick|title=X-Men: Apocalypse Set for May 27, 2016 |url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/180637-x-men-apocalypse-set-for-may-27-2016 |website=Superherohype.com|date= December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref> that he also produced and co-wrote with [[Simon Kinberg]], [[Dan Harris (screenwriter)|Dan Harris]], and [[Michael Dougherty]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Perry|last=Spencer|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/180853-bryan-singer-assembles-x2-writers-for-x-men-apocalypse |title=Bryan Singer Assembles X2 Writers for X-Men: Apocalypse |website=superherohype.com |date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=December 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Days of Future Past'' stars [[Hugh Jackman]], [[James McAvoy]], [[Michael Fassbender]], [[Nicholas Hoult]], [[Jennifer Lawrence]], and [[Evan Peters]] re-teamed with Singer for ''Apocalypse''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim|last=Stack|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/04/11/x-men-apocalypse-new-details|title='X-Men: Apocalypse': Who will return? What new mutants may appear? Scoop on the next X-Men film \u2013 Exclusive|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=April 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Tilly|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/05/21/quicksilver-will-have-expanded-role-in-x-men-apocalypse|title=QUICKSILVER WILL HAVE EXPANDED ROLE IN X-MEN: APOCALYPSE|website=[[IGN]]|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Singer, Bad Hat Harry Productions, and Same Name Productions started to collaborate on a documentary project with Guy Shalem. The documentary was set to explore the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] through the vantage point of a dynamic Arab-Israeli activist.<ref>{{cite web|first=Justin|last=Kroll|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/bryan-singer-israeli-palestinian-conflict-doc-1201558149|title=Bryan Singer to Develop Israeli-Palestinian Conflict Documentary (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fox announced that Singer would direct its version of ''[[20,000 Leagues under the Sea]]'', after having been asked to participate on the elaboration of the movie's script.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=McNary|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/bryan-singer-20000-leagues-under-the-sea-fox-1201696533|title=Bryan Singer's '20,000 Leagues Under the Sea' Lands at Fox|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 3, 2016|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the release of ''X-Men: Apocalypse'', Singer expressed interest in directing a solo [[Mystique (comics)|Mystique]] film starring Jennifer Lawrence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/05/x-men-jennifer-lawrence-mystique-spin-off|title=X-Men's Bryan Singer Really Wants a Solo Mystique Movie For Jennifer Lawrence|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|last=Robinson|first=Joanna|date=May 31, 2016|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, it was announced that Singer would direct the [[Queen (band)|Queen]] biopic ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/queen-movie-rami-malek-freddie-mercury-bryan-singer-bohemian-rhapsody-1201848910|title=Queen Movie Amping Up With Bryan Singer & Rami Malek As Freddie Mercury|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> He produced the film with [[Jim Beach]] and [[Graham King]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/08/22/freddie-mercury-biopic-bohemian-rhapsody-cast-playing-rest-queen|title= Freddie Mercury biopic Bohemian Rhapsody cast confirmed: who's playing the rest of Queen?|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=August 22, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> On December 1, 2017, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported that 20th Century Fox had temporarily halted production due to the \"unexpected unavailability\" of Singer, with sources saying that he had failed to return to the set after the Thanksgiving week. Producers were nervous about the state of production and started discussions about potentially replacing him, at which point cinematographer [[Newton Thomas Sigel]] may have stepped in to direct during Singer's absence.<ref>{{cite magazine|first1=Borys|last1=Kit|first2=Kim|last2=Masters|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fox-halts-production-queen-biopic-due-bryan-singer-absence-1063710|title=Fox Halts Production on Queen Biopic Due to Bryan Singer Absence|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> Singer's absence was reportedly due to \"a personal health matter concerning [him] and his family,\" and Singer's representatives stated that he was visiting his ill mother.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42193912 Bryan Singer: Illness forces director to stop work on Freddie Mercury film] BBC News. Retrieved December 1, 2017.</ref> However, other sources stated that the film's lead actor [[Rami Malek]] and the crew had grown tired of Singer's behavior; Singer had reportedly shown up late to set on multiple occasions, and having repeatedly clashed with Malek.<ref>{{cite web|first=Molly|last=Freeman|url=https://screenrant.com/bryan-singer-bohemian-rhapsody-halts-production/ |title=Fox Halts Production on Bryan Singer's Queen Biopic Bohemian Rhapsody|website=[[Screen Rant]]|date=December 1, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, 2017, Singer was fired as director with about two weeks remaining in principal photography.<ref>{{cite magazine|first1=Borys|last1=Kit|first2=Kim|last2=Masters|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bryan-singer-fired-directing-queen-biopic-set-chaos-1063977|title=Bryan Singer Fired From Directing Queen Biopic After On-Set Chaos (Exclusive)|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Singer's replacement [[Dexter Fletcher]] is quoted saying he came in and \"just finished it up, really.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wakeman|first=Gregory|title=Dexter Fletcher talks replacing Bryan Singer as 'Bohemian Rhapsody' director|url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/dexter-fletcher-on-becoming-bohemian-rhapsody-director|website=Metro US|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> 20th Century Fox terminated his [[Bad Hat Harry Productions]] deal with the studio. Singer still received directorial credit for ''Bohemian Rhapsody'' due to a [[Directors Guild of America]] ruling that only a sole director can receive credit.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bryan-singer-gets-directing-credit-bohemian-rhapsody-1119361|title=Bryan Singer to Get Directing Credit on Queen Biopic 'Bohemian Rhapsody'|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 2017, Singer signed on to direct an action adventure pilot in the [[X-Men Universe]] entitled ''[[The Gifted (U.S. TV series)|The Gifted]]''. The show was broadcast on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and canceled after two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Oriana|last1=Schwindt|first2=Daniel|last2=Holloway|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-marvel-tv-series-1201968795/|title=Fox Orders X-Men Pilot With Bryan Singer Directing|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 24, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSinger is openly [[bisexual]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/movies/146448_x_men_director_bryan_singer_declares_new_interview_that_he_bisexual/index.html|title=Brian Singer: \"I am bisexual\"|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=May 14, 2014|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> and has said that growing up Jewish and a sexual minority influenced his movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/04/25/bryan_singer_x_men_2_interview.shtml|title=Interview: Bryan Singer|first=Stephen|last=Applebaum|work=[[BBC]]|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=October 7, 2006}}</ref> He and actress [[Michelle Clunie]] have a son who was born in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bryan Singer becomes father for first time|url=http://hub.contactmusic.com/story/bryan-singer-becomes-father-for-first-time_4522093|website=Contact Music|date=January 6, 2015|accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Sexual abuse allegations==\n{{See also|Me Too movement}}\n\n===1997 lawsuit===\nIn 1997, a 14-year-old extra accused Singer of asking him and other minors to film a shower scene in the nude for the film ''[[Apt Pupil (film)|Apt Pupil]]''.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune 1997\">{{cite news|last=Satoodeh|first=Ramin|title=Bryan Singer Allegations Part of Upcoming Sex Abuse Documentary|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-04-18/entertainment/sns-201404181737reedbusivarietyn1201159632-20140418_1_tribeca-film-festival-west-memphis-three-amy-berg|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=April 18, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> Two other adolescent boys, 16 and 17 years old, later supported the 14-year-old's claim.  The boys claimed trauma from the experience and filed a civil suit against the filmmakers alleging [[Intentional infliction of emotional distress|infliction of emotional distress]], [[negligence]], and [[privacy law|invasion of privacy]],<ref>{{cite news | last=Ascher-Walsh | first=Rebecca | url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,287669,00.html | title=A Clothes Call | newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=May 2, 1997 | accessdate=March 10, 2009}}</ref> and alleged that they were filmed for sexual gratification.<ref name=\"mottram223\">{{Harvnb|Mottram|2007|p=223}}</ref> While some sources state that the civil case was dismissed due to insufficient evidence,<ref name=\"picart116\">{{Harvnb|Picart|Frank|2006|p=116}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/bryan-singer-sexual-assault-rape-allegations-timeline-1201903868/ | title=The Bryan Singer Timeline: A History of Allegations and Defenses, from Troubled Films to Sexual Assault Claims| date=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bustle.com/p/director-bryan-singer-is-being-sued-over-allegations-of-sexual-assault-report-6779134 |title = Director Bryan Singer is Reportedly Being Sued over Allegations of Sexual Assault}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/i-considered-suicide-alleged-sex-abuse-victim-of-bryan-singer-tells-the-daily-beast |title = 'I Considered Suicide,' Alleged Sex Abuse Victim of Bryan Singer Tells the Daily Beast|newspaper = The Daily Beast|date = April 18, 2014|last1 = Teeman|first1 = Tim}}</ref> others indicate that it was settled out of court.<ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/03/bryan-singers-accusers-speak-out/580462/ |title = Nobody is Going to Believe You|journal = The Atlantic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/millennium-films-backs-bryan-singer-allegations-60608012 |title = Bryan Singer keeps directing gig following allegations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.apnews.com/e8275873de3b4218a50d6550b8e5006b |title = Bryan Singer faces allegations of sexual assault with minors|date = January 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://keprtv.com/news/entertainment/bryan-singer-keeps-directing-gig-following-allegations | title=Bryan Singer keeps directing gig following allegations| date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Los Angeles District Attorney's Office declined to press criminal charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/ap-bryan-singer-faces-allegations-of-sexual-assault-with-minors-2019-1|title=Bryan Singer faces allegations of sexual assault with minors|agency=[[Associated Press]]|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2014 lawsuits and allegations===\nIn April 2014, Singer was accused in a civil lawsuit of [[sexual assault]] of a minor. According to the suit filed by attorney [[Jeff Herman]], Singer is alleged to have [[Date rape|drugged and raped]] actor and model Michael Egan in Hawaii after meeting him at parties hosted by convicted [[sex offender]] [[Marc Collins-Rector]] in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brook|title=Suit Accuses Director of New 'X-Men' Film of Sexual Assault|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/18/business/media/in-lawsuit-director-of-new-x-men-film-is-accused-of-sexual-assault.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 17, 2014|accessdate=April 17, 2014}}</ref> Singer's attorney called the allegations \"completely fabricated\" and said Singer planned to [[counterclaim|countersue]].<ref name=\"Reuters 2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/18/usa-singer-abuse-idUSL2N0N919E20140418|title='X Men' director hit by sex abuse lawsuit weeks before premiere|first=Dana|last=Feldman|first2=Eric|last2=Kelsey|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=April 17, 2014|accessdate=April 18, 2014}}</ref> Singer denied the allegations in a statement, calling them \"outrageous, vicious, and completely false.\"<ref>{{cite web|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|url=http://time.com/77224/bryan-singer-sexual-abuse-allegations|title='X-Men' Director Singer: Sexual Abuse Allegations 'Outrageous'|date=April 25, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> On May 22, 2014, Singer's attorney presented evidence to [[Federal District Judge]] [[Susan Oki Mollway]] stating that neither Singer nor Egan were in Hawaii at the time.<ref>''Detroit Free Press'', Saturday, May 24, 2014, pg. 2D</ref> In early August 2014, Egan sought to withdraw his lawsuit via a Request for Court Order of Dismissal, and asked that it be granted \"without prejudice or an award of costs or fees, in the interest of justice.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/bryan-singer-accuser-seeks-withdraw-lawsuit-director-article-1.1894129|title=Bryan Singer accuser seeks to withdraw lawsuit against director|last=Dillon|first=Nancy|date=August 6, 2014|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|access-date=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612034812/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/bryan-singer-accuser-seeks-withdraw-lawsuit-director-article-1.1894129|archive-date=June 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, another lawsuit was filed by attorney Jeff Herman on behalf of an anonymous British man. Both Singer and producer [[Gary Goddard]] (who was also named separately in the first case) were accused of sexually assaulting \"John Doe No. 117.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://time.com/88234/bryan-singer-hollywood-scandal/|title=What The Bryan Singer Scandal Says About Hollywood|last=Pickert|first=Kate|date=May 5, 2014|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207064141/http://time.com/88234/bryan-singer-hollywood-scandal|archive-date=December 7, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, Goddard and Singer met the man for sex when he was a minor and engaged in acts of \"gender violence\" against him while in London for the premiere of ''[[Superman Returns]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paunescu|first=Delia|title=New Sexual-Abuse Lawsuit Filed Against Singer|date=May 4, 2014|website=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/new-sexual-abuse-lawsuit-filed-against-singer.html|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref> The charge against Singer in this case was dismissed, at the accuser's request, in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/bryan-singer-dropped-sex-abuse-case-brought-british-actor-article-1.1880661|title='X-Men' director Bryan Singer dropped from sex abuse case brought by British actor|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSinger was cited in the 2014 documentary film on child sexual abuse in Hollywood, ''[[An Open Secret]]'', but details of Egan's allegations were omitted after Egan withdrew his lawsuit during the film's production.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/bryan-singer-allegations-part-of-upcoming-sex-abuse-documentary-from-oscar-nominated-filmmaker-1201159632|title=Bryan Singer Allegations Part of Upcoming Sex Abuse Documentary|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 18, 2014|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=DeFore|accessdate=January 24, 2019|title='An Open Secret': Film Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/an-open-secret-film-review-749444|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=November 14, 2014}}</ref> Author [[Bret Easton Ellis]] alleged that two of his former partners had attended underage sex parties hosted by Singer and fellow director [[Roland Emmerich]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bryan-singer-sex-abuse-suit-699673|title=Bryan Singer Sex Abuse Suit: Bret Easton Ellis Says He Dated Two People Who 'Went Through World of Underage Parties' (Audio)|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2017 lawsuit===\nOn December 7, 2017, Cesar Sanchez-Guzman filed a lawsuit in [[Washington (state)|the state of Washington]] against Singer, alleging that he had been raped at age 17 by the director in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42278174|title=Bryan Singer: Director denies raping 17-year-old boy|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=December 8, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> Singer denied the allegations and removed himself from the public eye.<ref>{{cite web|first=Julia|last=Breakey|url=https://memeburn.com/2017/11/sexual-assault-bryan-singer-twitter|publisher=[[Memeburn]]|title=Sexual assault accused Bryan Singer deletes Twitter, online articles removed|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> After the lawsuit was announced, the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]] removed Singer's name from its Division of Cinema & Media Studies program,<ref>{{cite web|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/bryan-singer-usc-removing-name-film-school-1202223067|title=USC Dropping Bryan Singer's Name From Film School|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 8, 2017|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> an action which had been previously requested by students at the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/usc-students-launch-petition-to-remove-bryan-singers-na-1820233215|title=USC students launch petition to remove Bryan Singer's name from the school's media division|date=November 7, 2017|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Sanchez-Guzman's bankruptcy trustee Nancy James recommended that a $150,000 settlement be approved, citing the absence of evidence that Singer attended the yacht party where the alleged assault took place. Singer's attorney Andrew Brettler said that Singer has maintained his innocence and that the \"decision to resolve the matter with the bankruptcy trustee was purely a business one\". Much of the settlement would go towards paying creditors and the administrators of the case, with the remainder allocated to Sanchez-Guzman.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maddaus |first=Gene |title=Bryan Singer to Pay $150,000 to Resolve Rape Claim |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/bryan-singer-sanchez-guzman-settlement-1203241557/ |newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]  |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 allegations ===\nOn January 23, 2019, Alex French and Maximillian Potter published an [[Investigative journalism|investigative report]] in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' in which four more men alleged that Singer sexually assaulted them when they were [[Statutory rape|underage]].<ref name=\"The Atlantic 2019\">{{cite news|first1=Alex|last1=French|first2=Maximillian|last2=Potter|accessdate=January 23, 2019|title=Nobody Is Going to Believe You|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/03/bryan-singers-accusers-speak-out/580462/|newspaper=[[The Atlantic]]|date= March 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=January 23, 2019|title=Bohemian Rhapsody Director Bryan Singer Accused of Sexually Assaulting Four Underage Boys|url=https://people.com/movies/bryan-singer-sexual-misconduct-allegations-four-new-men/|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=January 23, 2019|first=Ale|last=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Andreas|last1=Wiseman|accessdate=January 23, 2019|title=Bryan Singer Hit With New Allegations Of Sex With Underage Boys in Atlantic Report|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/bryan-singer-atlantic-sex-boys-bohemian-rhapsody-1202539927/|date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> The article also claimed that Sanchez-Guzman's 2017 lawsuit was stalled when Singer's legal team reported Sanchez-Guzman to the [[Internal Revenue Service]] and to [[US immigration]] officials, although this was disputed by one of Singer's lawyers.<ref name=\"The Atlantic 2019\"/><ref>{{cite web|first1=Daniel|last1=Kreps|accessdate=January 24, 2019|title='Bohemian Rhapsody' Director Bryan Singer Faces New Accusations of Sexual Abuse, Rape|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/bryan-singer-accusation-sexual-abuse-rape-atlantic-783208/|date=January 23, 2019|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref> In response to the men's allegations, Singer denied any association with them and described the journalists as \"[[homophobic]]\".<ref name=\"The Atlantic 2019\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Gene|last=Maddaus|accessdate=January 23, 2019|title=Bryan Singer Hit With Fresh Allegations of Sex With Underage Boys|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/bryan-singer-allegations-sex-underage-boys-1203115090/|date=January 23, 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 24, 2019|title='Bohemian Rhapsody' director Bryan Singer faces new allegations of sexual misconduct, issues forceful denial|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/01/23/bohemian-rhapsody-director-bryan-singer-faces-new-allegations-sexual-misconduct-issues-forceful-denial/|website=The Washington Post|first=Sonia|last=Rao|date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the renewed allegations, [[GLAAD]] withdrew ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]]''{{'}}s nomination for the year's [[GLAAD Media Award]] in the [[GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Film \u2013 Wide Release|Outstanding Film \u2013 Wide Release]] category and stated, \"Singer's response to ''[[The Atlantic]]'' story wrongfully used 'homophobia' to deflect from sexual assault allegations\".<ref name=\"Variety GLAAD\">{{cite web|first1=Matt|last1=Donnelly|accessdate=January 25, 2019|title='Bohemian Rhapsody' Loses GLAAD Award Nomination Over Bryan Singer Accusations (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bohemian-rhapsody-loses-glaad-award-nomination-bryan-singer-1203116481/|date=January 24, 2019|website=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=January 25, 2019|title=Bohemian Rhapsody excluded by award show|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-46998838|date=January 25, 2019|website=BBC}}</ref> [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] released a statement on Twitter applauding the decision, stating, \"The recent allegations regarding Bryan Singer's behavior are horrifying and MUST be taken seriously and investigated.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=TIME'S UP|accessdate=January 25, 2019|title=TIME'S UP on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/TIMESUPNOW/status/1088568653711196160|date=January 24, 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety GLAAD\" /><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 25, 2019|title=GLAAD awards drops 'Bohemian Rhapsody' after sex abuse accusations against Bryan Singer|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2019/01/24/bryan-singer-sex-abuse-allegations-cost-bohemian-rhapsody-awards-nod/2672171002/|website=USA Today|first=Bill|last=Keveney}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Petrana|last1=Radulovic|accessdate=January 25, 2019|title=Despite new sexual misconduct accusations, Bryan Singer still set to direct Red Sonja movie|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/24/18196562/bryan-singer-red-sonja-sexual-misconduct|date=January 24, 2019|website=Polygon}}</ref> On February 6, the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] removed Singer's name from ''Bohemian Rhapsody''{{'}}s nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film]] due to the allegations against him.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=February 7, 2019|title=Bafta removes Bryan Singer from nomination|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-47147570|date=February 6, 2019|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 7, 2019|title=BAFTA drops Bryan Singer from 'Bohemian Rhapsody' nomination over sexual misconduct allegations|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/02/06/bafta-drops-bryan-singer-bohemian-rhapsody-nomination-over-sexual-misconduct-allegations/|website=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, Millennium Films stated that ''[[Red Sonja (film)#Remake|Red Sonja]]'', a film that Singer had been attached to direct, was no longer on their slate of films, although the company's founder [[Avi Lerner]] had earlier defended hiring Singer despite the allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bryan-singer-red-sonja-movie-delayed-millennium-1203135878/|title=Bryan Singer's 'Red Sonja' Movie Delayed Amid Controversy|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|date=February 11, 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Year\n! rowspan=2 | Title\n! colspan=4 | Credited as\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n! width=65 |director\n! width=65 |[[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=65 |Writer\n! width=65 |Actor\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Lion's Den (1988 film)|Lion's Den]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Public Access]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1998\n| ''[[Apt Pupil (film)|Apt Pupil]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n| ''Burn''\n| \n| {{yes}}\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| {{yes|Story}}\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]''\n| \n| \n| \n| {{yes}}\n| As Kelly\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[X2 (film